Recommendation:
We recommended to the management to:
Require the Municipal Accountant to adhere to the proper basis for recognizing fuel inventory and expenses, in compliance with IPSAS No. 12 and COA Circular No. 2015-009;
Implement immediate reconciliation among the records of the MAccO, GSO and motor pool fuel in charge to establish correct inventory balance as of December 31, 2024. Afterwards, require the Municipal Accountant to draw Journal Entry Voucher (JEV) supported with working papers to effect the necessary adjusting entries, if warranted;
Instruct the General Services Officer (GSO)-designate and Gasoline Clerk to conduct a monthly physical inventory of fuel using a measuring device and reconcile the actual quantity on hand with accounting records; and,
Strictly enforce compliance with COA Circular No. 77-61 to strengthen internal control by maintaining complete documentation, including Daily Gas Issue Records, Gasoline Control Cards, Summary of RIVs, and Monthly Reports of Official Travels and Fuel Consumption.

We recommended to the management to:

a. Instruct the Municipal Assessor and the GSO-Designate to coordinate in expediting the transfer of acquired real properties in favor to the name of the municipality by securing the TCTs pursuant to COA Circular 92-386 to avoid land disputes in the future;

b. Remind the designated GSO to take custody of TCTs and other related documents kept by the Municipal Treasurer’s Office;

c. Require the Municipal Accountant to undertake an in-depth analysis and reconciliation of the Land account to enhance the completeness and accuracy of the said affected account and to provide a separate relevant disclosure in the Notes to Financial Statements as required by IPSAS 17 that would be beneficial in the decision-making of the users of the financial statements;

d. Direct the Municipal Accountant to immediately draw a Journal Entry Voucher to derecognize the portion of land already donated to PNP, substantiated with pertinent documents.

We recommended to the management to take the following actions:

1. Direct the BAC Secretariat to prepare and submit APP-CSE before the deadline set by existing rules and regulations;

2. Instruct the BAC Secretariat to create an account in mPhilGEPS for the uploading of the APP-CSE;

3. Procure common-use office supplies and equipment via mPHILGEPS or to nearest PS-DBM Regional Depot for a more cost efficient and time efficient means, unless justified by the non-availability of stocks at PS-DBM to resort to shopping mode of procurement; and,

4. The Municipal Accountant to ensure that disbursement vouchers in payment to suppliers other than the PS-DBM are supported with certificates of non-availability of stocks (CNAS).

We recommended that the BAC:
To revisit the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations to re-acquaint themselves of their responsibilities;
To be mindful of the timeline of procurement activities to avoid unreasonable delays;
To take the post-qualification process seriously to filter out those bidders with doubtful credentials;
To explain the inconsistency in the declaration of the eligibility among the following projects during the opening of bids: Level III Water system Rehabilitation of Distribution Pipeline with contract price of P7,059,855.60, Rehabilitation of Water System from 6” Dia pipe to 8” Dia pipe with contract price of P5,495,502.60, and Level III Water System, Rehabilitation of Distribution Pipeline from Imbatug - Nicdao Phase I, Baungon, Bukidnon with contract price of P10,176,298.20;
To explain the reason for the failure of the new BAC members to validate and verify the previously noted deficiency (undeclared asset in financial statement which do not collaborate with the other submitted documents) by the old BAC members during the post-qualification stage so as to facilitate the completion of our auditorial review.

We recommended to the Management the following:
Send positive confirmations to creditors to verify the amounts recorded in the books;
Gather and evaluate supporting documents and institute necessary adjusting entries, in case of error;
Pay the liabilities if supporting data and/or confirmation letters would prove the validity of claims against the LGU; and
Reverse the accounts payable accounts if supporting documents and detailed evaluation warrant the same.

